  1. The version of Rocket you're using. Ensure it's the latest, if possible.
rocket = "0.3.0"
rocket_codegen = "0.3.0"
rocket_contrib = "0.3.0"

  2. The operating system (distribution and version) where the issue occurs.
Ubuntu 17.04

  3. A brief description of the bug that includes:
This example in the docs doesn't work because Json does not impl FromRequest. (unless you see something wrong in my code below)
[Invoking Request Guards from Requests](https://api.rocket.rs/rocket/struct.Request.html#example-15)

  4. How you uncovered the bug. Short, reproducible tests are especially useful.
I'm using the Json module in my requests handlers, like in the following code.  I expected it to behave like a normal request guard.
```rust
use rocket_contrib::{Json, Value};
use rocket::State;

use models::{User,UserMessage,BLANK_USER_MESSAGE};
use state::MongoUsers;


#[post("/new", format = "application/json", data = "<message>")]
pub fn new_user(message: Json<UserMessage>, mongo_users: State<MongoUsers>) -> Result<Json<Value>,Json<Value>> {
```

I'm trying to use it in my new request guard like in the code below (None => branch of the match)
```rust
use rocket::{Outcome, State};
use rocket::http::{Cookie, Status};
use rocket::request::{self, Request, FromRequest};
use rocket_contrib::{Json, Value};

use models::{User, UserMessage};

impl<'a, 'r> FromRequest<'a, 'r> for User {
    type Error = ();

    // TODO: Maybe the success outcome is the list of permissions the user has
    fn from_request(request: &'a Request<'r>) -> request::Outcome<User, ()> {
        // does a cookie already exist?
        match request.cookies().get("auth") {
            Some(authCookie) => {
                // TODO:  What does the authcookie look like?
                println!("{:?}",authCookie);
                let test_user = User {
                        id: "test".to_string(),
                        name: "test".to_string(),
                        email: "test".to_string(),
                        password: "test".to_string(),
                        is_admin: false
                };
                return Outcome::Success(test_user);
            },
            None => {
                // check for credentials in UserMessage
                // hmmm, why won't this work?
                let outcome = request.guard::<Json<UserMessage>>();
                // TODO: not sure what this Returns
                // match on the outcome, if we can validate creds in usermessage then ok
                //println!("{:?}",outcome);
                return Outcome::Failure((Status::Unauthorized, ()));
            }
        }
    }
}
```

